1
00:00:00,520 --> 00:00:25,902
Namo tassa bhagavato harhato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harhato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harhato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:26,422 --> 00:00:31,211
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,036 --> 00:00:38,966
The word this evening is Sanyojana.

4
00:00:38,985 --> 00:00:46,079
S-A-M-Y-O-J-A-N-A And it translates as the fetters, chains, something which binds us.

5
00:00:46,939 --> 00:00:47,942
And there are ten of them.

6
00:00:50,234 --> 00:00:51,295
And I'll just go through them.

7
00:00:51,976 --> 00:01:09,930
Personality belief, skeptical doubt, clinging to mere rules and rituals, sensuous craving, ill will, craving for fine material existence, craving for immaterial existence, conceit, restlessness and ignorance.

8
00:01:11,783 --> 00:01:34,411
And what's particularly interesting about the ten fetters is that they are joined with the four paths and fruits of the four sainthoods which are, just very quickly, stream entrance, once returner, non-returner and arahat, the free, self-enlightened one.

9
00:01:34,430 --> 00:01:40,558
So what the Buddha is saying here is that every time you make one of these paths and fruits

10
00:01:41,415 --> 00:01:53,772
one of these fetters begin to drop away so the insight which we get every time we enter one of these fruits destroys

11
00:01:54,004 --> 00:01:55,686
the ability to go back on it.

12
00:01:56,929 --> 00:02:00,733
This will become pretty obvious to you as we go along.

13
00:02:00,754 --> 00:02:08,383
So, if we just take the first three, because the first three are connected with the first path and fruit of Sotapanna.

14
00:02:08,903 --> 00:02:10,506
Sotapanna means stream entry.

15
00:02:11,146 --> 00:02:16,734
So, at this point, the person becomes a noble person.

16
00:02:16,753 --> 00:02:22,981
When we talk about an Ariya, a noble person is somebody who has gone beyond the ordinary,

17
00:02:23,332 --> 00:02:29,240
worldly consciousness and has touched upon the Nibbāna consciousness.

18
00:02:29,479 --> 00:02:30,181
That's what they've done.

19
00:02:30,942 --> 00:02:33,164
The Buddha talks about is a flash of lightning.

20
00:02:34,246 --> 00:02:38,069
So in a flash of lightning you see everything but it's only for that moment.

21
00:02:38,170 --> 00:02:48,723
It's not particularly deep but one thing that person knows which a person who has not had that does not know is that there is Nibbāna.

22
00:02:49,484 --> 00:02:52,867
There is a different transcendent state to ordinary consciousness.

23
00:02:54,889 --> 00:02:58,274
and it's upon that that these first three fetters go.

24
00:02:58,955 --> 00:03:04,122
So the first one is personality belief, sakāyā-ditti.

25
00:03:04,883 --> 00:03:11,450
It translates as believing this body personality, this human form, is Self.

26
00:03:14,134 --> 00:03:23,546
So some deep delusional misunderstanding has been snapped.

27
00:03:23,593 --> 00:03:26,616
It's not as though that's the end of self.

28
00:03:26,877 --> 00:03:30,500
In fact, some people who have this experience don't believe they've had it.

29
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:35,865
Even though the teacher tells them they've had it, they don't believe they've had it because their sense of self is still so great.

30
00:03:38,026 --> 00:03:40,269
Some people have it and they don't know they've had it.

31
00:03:41,971 --> 00:03:45,454
It's like it's just come to them.

32
00:03:45,514 --> 00:03:51,659
Like, for instance, somebody at the age of seven doesn't know that they've shifted the way they look at the world.

33
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:59,156
And for others it's a sort of wow experience and they can't believe what's happened.

34
00:04:00,377 --> 00:04:15,054
And there's no explanation for this in the scriptures or anything like that, but my own understanding is that if a person has already reached this state in a previous life, then in this life they're just making their way back up to where they left off in the last life.

35
00:04:15,655 --> 00:04:19,959
So in a sense it's just as natural for them as somebody of the age of seven.

36
00:04:20,091 --> 00:04:31,425
But if it's for the first time then it's such a veil that falls off the world that it seems just enormous to them.

37
00:04:31,444 --> 00:04:41,797
Such people tend to be happy to stay at that place not to move on so much but to just enjoy and absorb that sort of level of consciousness.

38
00:04:45,721 --> 00:04:48,124
And one of the insights

39
00:04:48,997 --> 00:04:56,911
of having that is, of course, that because there is this higher consciousness, we can say, we're not this body and mind.

40
00:04:57,492 --> 00:04:59,576
So something has snapped there, you see.

41
00:05:02,300 --> 00:05:03,822
The second one is skeptical doubt.

42
00:05:03,903 --> 00:05:10,675
So until we've personally experienced or personally had an Ibanic experience, we don't know.

43
00:05:10,975 --> 00:05:12,137
We don't know if the Buddha's

44
00:05:12,690 --> 00:05:15,855
is actually true.

45
00:05:16,254 --> 00:05:21,139
Whether it is an experience, we don't know by personal experience.

46
00:05:21,199 --> 00:05:25,264
And therefore, there's always a possibility of skeptical doubt.

47
00:05:27,548 --> 00:05:37,158
And remember, skeptical doubt has the power to stop us practicing, because we won't commit.

48
00:05:37,819 --> 00:05:41,483
That's when skeptical doubt becomes a real spiritual disease.

49
00:05:42,374 --> 00:05:48,122
When doubts just pass through our minds of, well, I can't do it, everybody else can, and I'm special that way.

50
00:05:48,843 --> 00:05:52,608
If you have that sort of doubt, then it sometimes arises and passes away.

51
00:05:52,988 --> 00:05:57,555
But when it becomes a frame of mind, this doubt, then of course it becomes a barrier.

52
00:05:57,675 --> 00:06:02,281
You won't commit, you won't do, and therefore you don't move.

53
00:06:03,783 --> 00:06:08,630
That skeptical doubt is cut asunder, because now you know.

54
00:06:10,113 --> 00:06:10,473
That's it.

55
00:06:12,613 --> 00:06:15,317
And the third one is clinging to mere rites and rituals.

56
00:06:15,759 --> 00:06:26,735
So now that's the understanding that rites and rituals in themselves are material to the path of liberation.

57
00:06:26,755 --> 00:06:36,190
So if you go back to the Buddha's time, and even today you'll find people thinking that their karma is washed away by standing in the Ganges or doing something like that.

58
00:06:37,211 --> 00:06:41,017
And that's a wrong understanding of rites and rituals.

59
00:06:41,790 --> 00:06:45,416
People go overboard with that sometimes.

60
00:06:45,456 --> 00:06:48,742
They think that all rites and rituals are there for a complete waste of time.

61
00:06:49,283 --> 00:06:50,947
But the Buddha didn't think that.

62
00:06:51,247 --> 00:06:56,016
I mean, we have quite a rite to go through when you want to join the order, for a start.

63
00:06:56,497 --> 00:07:00,684
There's a whole series of things, taking refuges and precepts, for instance.

64
00:07:00,704 --> 00:07:02,026
It's something that he instigated.

65
00:07:02,107 --> 00:07:06,735
In fact, it was the second way into ordaining to the order.

66
00:07:07,829 --> 00:07:13,819
Well, the first way was when somebody would say to him, you know, I'd like to be a disciple, I'd like to follow you.

67
00:07:14,319 --> 00:07:18,146
And his response was, Ehi, Ehi Pasigo, come and try.

68
00:07:18,165 --> 00:07:20,108
That was it, that was the ordination.

69
00:07:21,290 --> 00:07:23,033
You know, just come and try, stay with me.

70
00:07:23,754 --> 00:07:27,802
As the order grew a bit, then it became just slightly more formal.

71
00:07:27,982 --> 00:07:31,067
So they had to take the refuge and precepts, which we do in the evening.

72
00:07:31,767 --> 00:07:34,612
And then finally it turned into this rather...

73
00:07:35,216 --> 00:07:43,028
slightly elaborate ceremony which had a question-and-answer format to make sure that you were ready for going into the order.

74
00:07:44,752 --> 00:07:50,440
So it's not as though rites and rituals in themselves have no purpose.

75
00:07:52,384 --> 00:07:56,550
I personally think that they're very good for setting a mood, so I always start a retreat

76
00:07:57,002 --> 00:07:59,326
you know, taking reference precepts.

77
00:08:00,367 --> 00:08:06,196
People take them at their own level, but it's like it's a gateway and sort of helps you move into it.

78
00:08:06,516 --> 00:08:18,713
So even in the morning, like when you do your refuge, when you're doing your two-hour morning practice, you see, to sort of begin with a little bowing or something, which is an entrance into it.

79
00:08:19,454 --> 00:08:24,882
So, but that itself, of course, is not specifically material.

80
00:08:24,947 --> 00:08:27,511
to the process of liberation.

81
00:08:27,752 --> 00:08:31,476
What's material to the process of liberation is seeing things as they really are.

82
00:08:31,497 --> 00:08:32,918
It's the insight which liberates.

83
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:41,090
But so long as there's some sort of belief, then it becomes a little barrier, because some of your energy goes into believing it.

84
00:08:41,710 --> 00:08:50,381
And interestingly enough, it also manifests in the way that a person's relationship to the technique they're using in meditation.

85
00:08:51,154 --> 00:08:53,177
The technique becomes a sort of mystique.

86
00:08:53,217 --> 00:08:56,884
It becomes a sort of, you know, if you haven't got the technique right, you can't make it.

87
00:08:57,404 --> 00:09:03,836
So people like that are very worried about, you know, whether they've really got the technique right and how they're doing it properly.

88
00:09:05,177 --> 00:09:06,119
And of course they miss the point.

89
00:09:06,139 --> 00:09:12,409
They're turning the technique itself into a sort of little ritual whereby they can attain liberation.

90
00:09:12,429 --> 00:09:15,153
Whereas the technique is only there to support mindfulness.

91
00:09:15,173 --> 00:09:15,575
Full stop.

92
00:09:16,034 --> 00:09:17,618
You're supposed to let go of it after a while.

93
00:09:19,149 --> 00:09:31,184
So, these first three fetters, the one where this deep identity we have with this human form, that's cut asunder.

94
00:09:32,225 --> 00:09:38,474
The skeptical doubt completely disappears in the sense that one now knows what the Buddha was talking about.

95
00:09:39,654 --> 00:09:42,960
And rites and rituals are put into the right perspective.

96
00:09:42,980 --> 00:09:44,922
We're not clinging to them for wrong reasons.

97
00:09:47,922 --> 00:09:58,910
And these are the three fetters that go when a person has what we call this sotapanna, this stream-entrant experience.

98
00:10:01,995 --> 00:10:03,398
And that's how they're connected.

99
00:10:03,418 --> 00:10:08,004
These fetters are connected to the process of liberation.

100
00:10:08,284 --> 00:10:12,211
So here you see what it is you're liberated from.

101
00:10:12,230 --> 00:10:14,735
When we talk about liberated, what are you liberated from?

102
00:10:14,774 --> 00:10:15,777
This is what you're liberated from.

103
00:10:16,116 --> 00:10:20,123
The Sotapanna is liberated from these three fetters.

104
00:10:25,418 --> 00:10:52,033
and remember they can't go back on it you can't go back on the level of consciousness that's it wherever they're born in whatever state they're born they'll always rise to that point you can't lose that knowledge so I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you be liberated

105
00:10:52,570 --> 00:11:01,416
from these three lower fetters sooner rather than later.

